rings to light new correspondence between Hamilton and her friends, revealing the importance of female networks to an artist’s well being. Her letters from abroad, in particular, bring a woman’s perspective into the immediate post-war period and give voice to trying conditions. Hamilton’s career is situated within the context of her peers Florence Carlyle, Emily Carr, and Sophie Pemberton with whom she shared a Canadian and European experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPainterszCanadavBiography. 0aWar artistszCanadavBiography. 0aWomen painterszCanadavBiography. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918vArt and the war. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Artists, Architects, Photographers.2bisacsh1 aMcKinnon, Sarah M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755525140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887555251423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887555251/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles